segments.text: attitude of people.

One of the recollections I have, and one of the funny meetings we had, former students, we used to have our annual meeting up in the YMCA Chapel, before the Student Center was built, and we proposed as an objective of the development fund, the golf course.
Well, man, if we had opposed adultery, we could have turned up a hornet's nest.
All these old timers, the silliest thing I ever heard of.
Expect students to get out there and hit that silly ball right in the ground out there.
An old man got up and said, our milk counts down there 25 cents an hour, and I'd all propose to be a part of anything as frivolous as a golf course.
But the younger ones prevailed.
And, uh, but now that wouldn't, uh, that wouldn't frighten anybody about a golf course.
They would take a thing about it.
Spending a lot of money on a golf course right now.
Yeah.
Um, I believe also you were involved in, in starting of the, uh, Opportunity Award Scholarship Fund.
Yeah, we started that.
What, uh, how did that happen to come about?

Well, of course, we'd operated a loan fund through the years, but it had become increasingly difficult to finance enough through the loan fund, so we hit on the idea of combining a job with a scholarship, which was designed to give a student about two-thirds of
the year's cost, and then he had to get the rest of it from home or summer employment.
And we just hit on the name, Opportunity of War.
So when a boy was selected to get one, he was also guaranteed a job, mostly in the mess hall.
It goes through the years.
Mess hall waiters, that job was the tops of all the student jobs.
I don't think, I don't even have to miss all the waiters anymore.
Well, they're more busboys than they are waiters now, I believe.
Yeah, but in those days, that was the top job on the campus, and it paid so much a month and board.
So it was, and they would set aside a certain number of these jobs for opportunity award winners.
So it was a case in which the college and the association were working together.
Working together, yeah.
The college would provide a job, and then you would provide some supplementary money for them.
How much did you provide for each student in the beginning, do you remember?
That was for a year or for a semester?
That was for a year.
In that time, we figured a student could go a year for about $1,000.
He couldn't own an automobile and live in an apartment, but he could go to school.
Well, I imagine at that point there weren't very many of them who had automobiles.
Well, I don't think we'd have ever given one an opportunity award if he had an automobile.
He wouldn't have needed one, would he?
Uh-uh.
Let's see.
What...
We mentioned, talked a bit earlier about this, the annual giving program evolving into the development fund.
What kind of originally or initially was the purpose of the development fund?
Well, basically to have some money to give to the college for

purposes that they needed but which state funds were not available of course the state's gotten very liberal these days as far as they used to have riders on that appropriation you couldn't spend any money for a golf course or you couldn't spend any money for uh this that or the other now apparently they can spend money for anything well there's still a lot of things which you can't take money from uh but uh so it actually it was it was uh
The association then sort of set up a separate fund.
Well, we had to take our expenses out of that fund.
Well, just like when we started with the student union.
I don't know that we had any idea how much it cost when we started it.
But it was something that the college needed.
Most schools had them by that time.
They were pretty big.
Now they're so accustomed, everybody's so accustomed to it, they don't make anything.
And we were ambitious like everybody else.
Now what I was getting at is you had the annual giving program.
and you discontinued the membership dues.
We discontinued the dues, yeah.
And you had the annual giving program.
So I was wondering, did you then just take all the money you got in and put it into the development fund?
Yeah, yeah.
That's all the income we had.
Oh, we had a few investments.
We had some endowment funds, not many, not much.
And advertising in the Texas Aggie, a few miscellaneous sources.
So I was misled.
I thought perhaps you had a special fundraising effort to create the development fund.
No, no, we just made the change and started soliciting on a different basis and it worked out all right.
And then
By 1947, it apparently had devolved to it enough of a program in which, well, I guess even before that, because you succeeded Henderson Shuffler as the executive director of the development fund.
Yeah, yeah.
And also the executive director of special gifts and bequests.
Yeah.
This was for the college, or was it still for the Association of Former Students?
Well, for the college, yeah.
So then the college got money for the development fund as well as the Association of Former Students?
Well, we got into, I guess, a little difficulty on the name.
The association had called their money raising efforts the development fund.
And then when we set up the college office, and we were instrumental in setting that up, talking them into...
put the man in there and seek special gifts for the college.
They called that the development fund.
It was supposed to seek these special gifts and bequests, things of that sort.
And worked real closely with the former student association.
Well, somewhere, I don't believe the former students call theirs the development fund anymore.
I think they call that other office the development program.
That's Bob Walker's office now.
And former students call theirs annual giving.
But there was a confusion there as to names.
So then the development fund of which you were executive director was separated from the former students by the time you were involved in it.
And then that was to, was that for, say, if a professor had a research project
you would assist him in obtaining funding, or did you assist only college programs in obtaining funding?
Well, we hadn't gotten into assisting the individual research program.
That was done by the dean and other people.
Mostly, the effort was to get bequests and, oh, industrial grants and things of that sort.
This would be an industrial grant for a department or for a college rather than an individual researcher.
The college has a lot of scholarship funds.
I say a lot, I don't know what it would total of, but it is a hell of a lot of individual scholarships.
And we'd always made a point of maintaining the integrity of each one of those funds, so the administration of them became quite a chore.
And that was under this office.
Now I believe Bob Logan handles that.
I'm not sure whether they're divided or not.
Maybe not.
I don't know.
I kind of believe Logan has the scholarship.
Bob Logan is director of student financial aid.
And all of that used to be under the development office.
It ground me down.
Well, yeah.
I believe what?
You probably had a committee that helped you decide who had what scholarship.
We had a scholarship committee.
And we had a general supervisory committee.
Development Board, we called it.
Um, what kind of, what relationship was there, say, between the, the Development Fund or Development Board and the Research Foundation, which started in the mid-40s?
Well, none.
None amounted thing.
I mean, there was no, there was no, uh,
difference between them.
I mean, there was no opposition.
Did you sometimes find yourself competing against each other for the same money?
I don't think so, really.
We weren't competing that strongly.
You mean the development fund?
Yeah.
And later on, I know some of the college people, the university people, felt like that we, maybe they've solved it now, that we ought to have a central office so that there would be no competition.

I never, I never think it's worthwhile, because you gotta set up a central office, then you gotta have another strata of executives, one thing or another, and these people you're seeking money for, from, well, take one of the instances, you say, well, suppose Fred Benson goes to the Elmwood Company and asks for some money, and the next day,
Donald Lindsay goes in there and asks them, I don't know what they're going to think.
And my position was, we don't care what they think.
They probably think, boy, they're after it.
And I said, they can say no just as easy as anybody in the world, and they don't bother them a damn bit.
And I don't think it ought to embarrass us.
But that's just one of those things that's bound to continue to occur.
Well, there is a central office of university research now in the vice president for academic affairs office.
Yeah, that's probably.
And that's a replacement for what was Dr. Suttles' vice president for research.
But I don't fully understand whether, say, something that's funneled through the research foundation, whether that goes through the university research office or not.
I don't know either.
But anyway, there is more of a central office now than there was in the past, anyway.
But I'm not so sure how much cooperation there is, say, between Dr. Berg, whose Office of University Research, and Bob Walker's Development Fund.
Well, I don't know either.
I don't know.

Bob, I would guess, was devoting most of his time to what I call special gifts, big quests, and somebody wants to give $50,000 to start a memorial fund or something of that sort, whereas this other officer would be more interested in research.
I've asked you about a number of specific things that were accomplished while you were with the Association of Farmer Students.
Are there some other things that were accomplished that you'd like to talk about?
You talked a little bit about mentioning the golf course, and that was one I had not asked you about.
You were there for quite a long while, and I know a lot of things happened.
I don't know.
Of course, they've had through the years various objectives of the development fund.
I don't recall all of them.
I think those were the groundbreaking ones right there that we mentioned.
I believe, of course, one of the other things which developed while you were
either, well, this would have been while you were with the development fund, and that was the construction of the All Faiths Chapel.
You were involved, I guess, in the raising of funds for that.
Was All Faiths a replacement for Guyon Hall as a place of worship?
I don't recall that it was, particularly.
that was, it just sounded like a pretty good objective.
Well, I guess even by that time, there was no, there was, well, even at that time, I guess there was really no worship service in Guyon Hall anymore on Sunday morning.
I don't think so.
With all of the local churches around.
I think Guyon Hall had outlived its
usefulness really, I guess.
Picture shows.
It was more of a social gathering place, a place of entertainment than a place of worship.
Of course commencement was held there.
I believe at one point you served a year's term as president of the American Alumni Council.
That was a position of, I suppose, a considerable amount of responsibility, but a considerable amount of honor too, was it not?
Well, mostly honor.
Mostly honor.
Mostly honor.
The council had and has an office in Washington, and the president has to,
but they have district meetings.
He makes each one of those district meetings.
I had a couple of board meetings here, but it's mostly an honor, really, I guess.
So the council then has, what, an executive director of its own that does most of the office?
Yeah, it's a day-to-day business.
What sort of services does the executive office of the Alumni Council provide to individual alumni organizations?
Oh, they have publications, and they put on these district meetings, and they put on an annual conference, and they maintain a library on alumni work, and that's
Mostly it.
I presume you say the executive director's office sort of puts on the annual meeting at which people from the various alumni organizations attend.
They then, I presume, are responsible for the executive director's office would be responsible for the program at which you get some of the ideas.
You come back to them.
That's right, yeah.
Of course, they always name some.
alumni secretary as director of the annual conference, but the office does the work.
The office does the work.
Would it be somebody in the vicinity?
Yeah, somebody in the vicinity.
There's a host.
Somebody acts as a host of the speaker.
Yeah, yeah.
Did that group ever meet here?
No, no, never have met in Texas.
The only time I met was Gulfport one year, as close as I recall.
Well, maybe that'll be something for us to strive for for the centennial year.
Well, they meet in the summer, and I wouldn't want anybody to come to Texas this summer.
Most people don't want to come to East Texas in the summertime.
That's right.
To have these national conferences of the American Alumni Council, I'd go to the board and ask for
or expenses to make the trip, travel expenses.
And I've made several of them.
And I remember one year, I had a board meeting.
I said, I want to go to this meeting.
I don't remember where it was.
And one crusty old gentleman spoke up.
He said, well, I said, I vote to provide the expenses with one provision.
He said, don't come back with any more of those goddamn big ideas.
So he was going to defeat your purpose in going before you ever left.
And that's where a lot of them came from.
Through the years, Texas A&M and Ohio State have had a relationship.
I may go back to old
Dean Francis, I don't know, D.W. Williams, just any number of Ohio State people here.
And I became acquainted with their alumni program and their alumni secretaries.
I had a couple of them.
And they were sharp.
They were way ahead of anybody else in the public school field.
So I got a lot of ideas from them.
and other people, of course.
There's a nice thing about alumni work.
You don't mind copying anybody because you're working in an entirely different clientele.
You're not going to compete with anybody.
I know one thing I wanted to ask you.
You mentioned that you picked up this idea of discontinuing dues and going to an annual giving program.
How much of an increase did you have in income?
We had a substantial increase.
I've forgotten how much, but I think our budget on the dues used to be about $25,000 a year or something like that.
I think we doubled that the first year we had the annual giving.
So there were any number of people who were happy to pay, who would pay $5 but could well afford more, but there really was not an opportunity.
Nobody asked them.
So if you give them the opportunity to open their purse and give you more, then they did.
I recall one, I think it was the first solicitation we sent out,
And we got a check back from a man that I knew personally.
He was a sort of a hell raiser, a drinker, one thing or another.
It was $500.
And the check was sort of messed up at one thing or another.
It was signed.
And I just couldn't believe what I was looking at.
So I called him up, and I said, Tommy, we got a check here for $500.
I just want to check with you to be sure it's right.
He said, you don't think I got $500?
I said, yeah.
I thought, you're pretty well fixed, man.
I said, yeah, I know you got $500.
Knowing you, I didn't know when and where you wrote this check.
He said, I wrote it in my office.
I said, my God, you're cashing.
Well, that puts you off to a good start.
Oh, yeah.
